# CODEOWNERS — trust-critical paths for credential-badges.
#
# DOCUMENT-ONLY gate (v1). This file records who must review changes to the
# paths below. It is intentionally NOT yet backed by branch-protection
# required-reviewers — a named team with >=2 required reviewers is deferred to
# productionization (deployment plan P1bis-09; "v1 has James as owner"). The
# cheap companion control is disabling force-push to the default branch.
#
# Scoped to Rungs 3-4 (did:web resolves; issuer Profile = AttestationHost),
# extended at Rung 8.3 with the served status-list JSON (per the plan's
# "later rungs extend this to the status-list JSON") and at Rung 8.6 with the
# kill-switch flip tool + runbook.

# The did:web DID document and its deterministic regenerator — this publishes
# the issuer signing key. A wrong or drifted key here silently breaks OB 3.0
# verification for every credential, so changes get a deliberate review. The
# whole /.well-known/** is gated (not just did.json) so any future sibling
# served on this forever-public path is reviewed too. did-pin.test.ts holds the
# pinned key constant (the actual invariant), so it is gated alongside.
/.well-known/**                @workshop-maybe
/tools/gen-did-json.ts         @workshop-maybe
/tools/did-pin.test.ts         @workshop-maybe

# The hosted OB 3.0 issuer Profile and the served JSON-LD contexts (Rung 4;
# v1 added by the context-version bump). The Profile declares the issuer as
# ["Profile","AttestationHost"] and names the did:web subject; the context
# DEFINES the AttestationHost extension term the Profile references. A wrong
# id, a dropped type, or an undefined term silently breaks strict-verifier
# expansion for every credential, so changes get a deliberate review.
# Published context versions are immutable forever — the sha256 pins live in
# tools/context-freeze.test.ts, which is gated alongside (same pattern as
# did-pin.test.ts). The whole /context/** is gated (matching /.well-known/**
# and /status/**) so any future version or stray sibling on this forever-
# public path is reviewed too. tools/issuer-profile.test.ts pins the profile
# shape invariant, so it is gated alongside as well.
/issuer/profile.jsonld         @workshop-maybe
/context/**                    @workshop-maybe
/tools/context-freeze.test.ts  @workshop-maybe
/tools/issuer-profile.test.ts  @workshop-maybe

# The served key-epoch BitstringStatusList credential and its builder/tests
# (Rung 8.3). A wrong bit here flags every credential signed under a key
# version as suspended in third-party verifier UIs; a wrong encodedList
# silently breaks status checks — changes get a deliberate review. The whole
# /status/** is gated so any future sibling on this forever-public path is
# reviewed too.
/status/**                             @workshop-maybe
/spike/signer-spike/status-list.ts     @workshop-maybe
/spike/signer-spike/status-list.test.ts @workshop-maybe

# The key-compromise kill-switch (Rung 8.6; deployment plan Decision 3 +
# CODEOWNERS glob set). The flip tool prepares the suspension flip for a whole
# key epoch — a wrong flip suspends every credential signed under a key
# version, including the flagship badge — and the runbook is the procedure the
# flip PR follows; both get a deliberate review.
/tools/flip-status-bit.ts        @workshop-maybe
/tools/flip-status-bit.test.ts   @workshop-maybe
/docs/runbooks/key-compromise.md @workshop-maybe

# Served-file allowlist controls. Adding a public, forever-served path must be
# a deliberate reviewed act — these four files are the allowlist surface
# (Dockerfile COPY, build-context re-includes, nginx location, CI gate).
/Dockerfile                    @workshop-maybe
/.dockerignore                 @workshop-maybe
/nginx/default.conf.template   @workshop-maybe
/scripts/ci/check-allowlist.sh @workshop-maybe
